\f0\fs24 \cf0 # HALO: Hybrid Algorithms Learning on Orbits\
\
[![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-blue.svg)](LICENSE)\
[![Framework](https://img.shields.io/badge/Powered%20by-PennyLane-yellow)](https://pennylane.ai/)\
[![Framework](https://img.shields.io/badge/Powered%20by-Scikit--Learn-orange)](https://scikit-learn.org/)\
\
This repository contains the official implementation of the **HALO** protocol, a Quantum Federated Learning (QFL) architecture designed to balance Differential Privacy ($\\epsilon$-DP) and convergence stability in resource-constrained environments (NISQ era).\
\
## 
\f1 \uc0\u55357 \u56524 
\f0  Overview\
\
Traditional Federated Learning models suffer from severe performance degradation when strict Differential Privacy (DP) noise is applied to their gradients. **HALO** addresses this instability by exploiting the periodic nature of Variational Quantum Circuits (VQCs).\
\
Key features of this implementation:\
1. **Geometric Saturation:** Utilizes angular parameters (bloch sphere rotations) to naturally absorb Laplacian noise, preventing the gradient explosion seen in classical Euclidean spaces.\
2. **Federated Learning Loop:** Simulates a distributed environment using a FedAvg-style aggregation.\
3. **Privacy vs. Utility Evaluation:** Includes built-in Membership Inference Attack (MIA) vulnerability scoring alongside standard accuracy metrics.\
4. **NISQ-Aware:** Compresses input features (64 pixels to 2 PCA coordinates) to operate efficiently on a 2-qubit architecture.\
\
